<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870721-0050 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief:CMS Energy Corp.</HL><DD> 07/21/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> CMS </IN><TEXT>   CMS Energy Corp., Jackson, Mich., said it will use an early-retirement program and attrition to reduce employment at its Consumers Power utility unit by 450, or about 4.5%, to trim annual operating costs by $18 million to $20 million beginning in 1988. The unit currently has 10,400 employees. CMS, formerly Consumers Power Co., ran into financial trouble in 1984 when it was forced to stop construction of its Midland nuclear power plant after years of cost overruns and construction errors. The holding company is converting part of the plant to a gas-fired facility in a joint venture with Dow Chemical Co. </TEXT></DOC>